results.reasoning: Transverse ultrasound images demonstrate a thin central intrauterine septum dividing the cavity into two hemicavities with placenta implanted on the septal/left side. This appearance is most consistent with a septate uterus with septal placental implantation; other anomalies (bicornuate/didelphys) would show a thick myometrial fundal cleft or separate uterine bodies, and synechiae are typically focal and irregular rather than a complete thin septum.

Chronic left lumbar pain with prolonged anemia and mild leukocytosis in an 8‑yr‑old, consistent with chronic suppurative renal disease. Imaging and history favor diffuse xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis (chronic nonfunctioning, inflammatory replacement of the kidney) over acute pyonephrosis, simple hydronephrosis, TB, or an aggressive renal tumor.

Pineal region midline homogenously enhancing mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus in an adult male; biopsy proven and excellent response to radiotherapy — classic for an intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma).

Postoperative CT-urography (excretory phase) demonstrates contrast extravasation from a distal ureter into a nearby pelvic fluid collection (opacified collection on excretory images and corresponding 3D reconstructions - arrow/arrowheads), consistent with iatrogenic ureteral injury with urinoma. Imaging findings exclude a simple seroma/loculated ascites or enteric leak (contrast pattern corresponds to urinary contrast).

Well-circumscribed cystic lesion at the volar wrist with high T2 signal and thin rim (fluid) and relation to the tendon sheath; lacks solid low-T2/hemosiderin signal or solid enhancement seen in GCTTS/fibroma/nodular fasciitis — most consistent with a ganglion cyst.

CT and US show a well-defined cystic mass in the left abdomen with wall hyperemia/enhancement and surrounding inflammatory changes in a patient without pancreatitis. Multiloculated/ cystic appearance and infection fit lymphangioma with inflammatory changes.

US images demonstrate a thin midline uterine septum dividing the amniotic sac into two hemicavities with placenta implanted on the septum. This is characteristic of a septate uterus with septal placental implantation; bicornuate/didelphys would show external fundal cleft or separate uterine bodies with thicker myometrium between horns, arcuate is only a shallow indentation, and synechiae are usually irregular/surgical bands.

Chronic left lumbar symptoms with long standing anaemia and leukocytosis, and imaging features of an enlarged nonfunctioning kidney with multiple dilated calyces (bear paw sign), staghorn calculus and perinephric inflammatory changes are classic for diffuse xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis.

Pineal midline, homogenously enhancing, hyperdense lesion causing obstructive hydrocephalus in an adult male with dramatic response to radiotherapy — classic for a radiosensitive intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma). Imaging lacks fat/calc of dermoid/teratoma, is solid not meningioma/tectal glioma, and pineoblastoma is typically heterogeneous and in younger patients.

Postoperative CT-urography demonstrates a pelvic fluid collection that becomes opacified on the excretory phase with direct contrast extravasation/communication from the distal ureter into the collection (visualized on axial and 3D reformats). This is diagnostic of an iatrogenic ureteral injury with urinoma; abscess/seroma/ascites or enteric leak would not show urinary contrast opacification tracking from the ureter.

MRI shows a well-defined volar wrist lesion with fluid-like high T2 signal and thin rim/septal enhancement consistent with a ganglion cyst. Lack of low T1/T2 signal or susceptibility (no hemosiderin) argues against GCTTS or fibroma of tendon sheath; nodular fasciitis/fibrous histiocytoma would be more solid and enhancing.

Cystic multiloculated mesenteric mass with thin enhancing wall and internal septa, adjacent inflammatory fat stranding and Doppler hyperemia in a febrile patient; imaging and clinical pattern match infected/inflamed mesenteric lymphangioma. Duplication cyst would show gut‑wall signature and bowel wall continuity; no pancreatitis history to support pseudocyst.
